column1: At close of business on 26 January 2022, will the upper limit of the Federal Reserve's target range for the federal funds rate be lower, the same, or higher than it was at close of business on 15 December 2021?
column6: ['Finance', 'Economic Policy']

Heard some analysts say that they expected a hike before the end of January, "a surprise announcement0", but doubted it based on the shock that would represent to markets, yet, given what we have seen in the markets this week, would it be a surprise or a shock? Are the markets already pricing a rate hike?
The money and bond markets have already discounted a move of over 25 basis points, which opens a window for early move by Fed.
Not going to change until March meeting too shocking to the system.

As the central bank prepares to remove emergency stimulus measures to support the economy, sustained inflation could force the Fed to move faster than it would like, before the labor market is fully healed. In newly released minutes from their latest policymaking meeting, Fed officials appear split, with “various” members arguing that interest rates should stay near zero for a couple of yearst, while “a number” said that rates would need to go up next year, with inflation most “likely to remain elevated in 2022 with risks to the upside.” A recent Fed survey suggests that consumer expectations for inflation are running at historic high.

The Fed's dot plot from the September meeting imply a central tendency of one hike in 2022, and Chair Powell has implied that tapering would need to end before hikes start. Further, the bar for rate hikes remains high per Chair Powell's most recent press conference. It is expected that tapering to end in mid-2022, even though it has not been announced tapering will start. Many market participants took the statement of "soon" to imply that tapering would be announced in November and start in December 2021.

+ Inflation will rise more than expected, so the Fed will raise the rate ( cheap price product from China will diminish, higher price for transportation, higher price for energy) - Covid -19 will still effect the world economy so the G-7 will try to stimulate it - High government debt need low rate - High government debt need devaluation of money

The next move will be lower to negative, not to raise rates. They will reduce quantitative easing a little bit, then the market will crash, then they will increase quantitative easing. They will never raise rates.

I find it a near 0 possibility they would go to negative rates. The most likely outcome is that it will remain the same. A rate increase is probable for 2022, but early in the year would seem a little too fast. Even in a fast inflation environment, the Fed has stated they would accelerate taper before looking to raise rates.
The fed needs to taper its bond buying before it raises interest rates, which should take 6-8 months [1]. I would expect the FOMC to move away from 0% by mid-to-late 2022, but not before then.
The rate will rise prior to the end of 2021, a quick additional rise is not likely.
